<br>
From National Office, Bat Approval List<br>
Posted by Ron Daniel on 2/19/2003, 5:16 pm <br>
66.26.90.74<br>
<br>
All USSSA Directors, <br>
I want to thank everyone for your patience as we implemented the new and more stringent, extended BPF USSSA bat standard for the 2003 softball season. To date, the bat manufacturers for the most part have cooperated with us and been helpful in this process. Without their cooperation and the guidance of our new general counsel, it would have been very difficult to implement the new rules for the 2003 season. <br>
<br>
The USSSA has extended its 1.20 BPF bat standard for 2003 licensing purposes. In previous years, the test was applied only to brand new bats and only at the center of percussion. The new extended 2003 BPF standard is also applied to bats after use and applied to points other than the center of percussion. The extended BPF rules were chosen to ensure clever or even accidental engineering for improved performance off of the center of percussion and/or for used bats would not defeat the purpose of the BPF standard. While the bat manufacturers were generally cooperative in implementing the new test, testing still takes time. In the fall of 2002, we let the manufacturers know that these rule changes were coming, and in December of 2002, announced the new extended BPF rules. Because we did not announce the rule until December 2002 and because testing takes time, the first listing of USSSA licensed 2003 bats did not occur until February 19, 2003. There simply was no way in our view to fairly list licensed bats prior to that date.<br>
<br>
Having implemented the new rules, we are by no means through with these issues. Even under the stricter 2003 USSSA softball bat rules, the bats that will be licensed in 2003 USSSA play will still include high performance bats. While we might change the standard again in the future, such changes most likely would be designed with grandfathering of 2003 and even 2004 bats and with implementation after a relatively longer period of notice of the change being given to the manufacturers, perhaps 12 months <br>
<br>
If you have any concerns regarding the level of USSSA play, please refer to your rulebook that allows you to impose a limit on the ball used in USSSA play: .47 cor. with a 375# maximum compression cap. Now that we have a new extended BPF bat standard, the lower compression ball becomes your first and best response to concerns you may have with regard to the appropriate level of USSSA softball play. <br>
<br>
For the list of 2003 USSSA licensed bats go to www.usssa.com - click on legal bats (last tab on left side). <br>
<br>
<br>
Don DeDonatis <br>
Executive Director/CEO<br>
